  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Xylem is the vascular tissue that conducts water and dissolved minerals from the roots upward through the plant body to the stems and leaves. It is composed of tracheids and vessel elements — elongated cells that, at functional maturity, are dead. Their cell walls remain as rigid, hollow tubes through which water moves by capillary action and transpiration pull. The xylem also provides structural support; wood is largely composed of accumulated secondary xylem.\n",
